	abstract = {Studies have consistently shown that crowds contribute to home advantage in the National Basketball Association (NBA) by inspiring home team effort, distracting opponents, and influencing referees. Quantifying the effect of crowds is challenging, however, due to potential co-occurring drivers of home advantage (e.g., travel, location familiarity). The present research aims to isolate the crowd effect by utilizing a ‘natural experiment’ created by the Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) pandemic, which eliminated crowds in 577 of 1080 (53.4\%) 2020/2021 NBA regular season games. Multi-level mixed models (fixed effect: crowds; random effects: team, opponent) were used to analyze the effect of crowds on performance metrics while controlling for team and opponent strength. We show, in games with crowds, home teams won 58.65\% of games and outrebounded (average rebound differential = 2.28 rebounds) and outscored (average points differential = 2.18 points) their opponents. This was a significant improvement compared to games without crowds, of which home teams won 50.60\% of games (p {\textless} .001) and failed to outrebound (average rebound differential = -0.41 rebounds, p {\textless} .001) or outscore (average points differential = -0.13 points, p {\textless} .05) their opponents. Further, the crowd-related increase in average rebound differential fully mediated the relationship between crowds and average points differential. Finally, among games with crowds, crowd size and density were not related to performance. Taken together, these results suggest that home advantage in the 2020/2021 NBA season was predominately driven by the mere presence of home crowds and their influence on the effort exerted to rebound the basketball. These findings are of considerable significance to a league where marginal gains can have immense competitive, financial, and historic consequences.},
